"Written evidence submitted by Liberty (LAI 0027)&#xa0;\nIntroduction&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nThe Residency Test&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n              \n              \n              \n              \n              \n              \n              \n              \n“It can be persuasively argued that a prohibition of legal aid\n is within the ambit of article 6, for the purposes of engaging article 14 a\nnd so precluding unjustifiable \ndiscrimination… Ultimately, the exclusion would itself fail a justification test because it denies practical and effective justice\n.”\n&#xa0;\nThe legal advi\nce further notes that this aspect of the proposals\n:\n&#xa0;\n“does not focus on legitimacy of resort to the Court, the nature of the issue \n[or] \nthe viability of the argument. Being a foreigner does not indicate a lesser need, or a lesser justification, for effecti\nve access to the Court.”\n \n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;Prisoners&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;Judicial Review funding&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n“we had 11,359 applications for judicial review. In the end 144 were successful and all of the rest of them tied up government lawyer\ns, local authority lawyers in time, in expense for a huge number of cases of which virtually none were successful.”\n \n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nBorderline Cases&#xa0;&#xa0;Conclusion&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nSeptember 2013\n \nSee \nLiberty’s Response to the MOJ Consu\nltation Transforming Legal Aid\n,a\nvailable at: \nhttp://www.liberty-human-rights.org.uk/pdfs/policy13/liberty-s-response-to-the-moj-s-consultation-on-legal-aid-2013.pdf\n Where necessary to comply with obligations under EU or international law, the Government relies on the exceptional funding regime s\net out in \nthe Legal Aid, Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders Act\n 2012, which provides that civil legal aid funding will be available\n.\n \nMoJ consultation paper: \n‘\nTransforming Legal Aid: Next Steps\n’\n, \nSeptember 2013, \npara 2.14.\n See widespread reporting o\nf alleged ill-treatment, for example: \nhttp://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-24106338\n and \nhttp://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2013/sep/14/detainees-yarls-wood-sexual-abuse\n.\n \n MoJ consultation paper: \n‘Transforming legal aid: delivering a more credibl\ne and efficient system,’ \nApril 2013, para 3.44.\n Joint Opinion, The Legality of the Proposed Residence Test for Civil Legal Aid, Michael Fordham QC, Ben Jaffey and Ravi Mehta, Blackstone Chambers, 28 May 2013, para 2. Available on Liberty’s website.\n Ibi\nd., para 4.\n Ibid.\n Ibid., para 3.\n Ibid.\n Article 6\n, the European Convention on Human Rights (“the\n ECHR\n”)\n.\n Article 5(4) ECHR: ‘Everyone who is deprived of his liberty by arrest or detention shall be entitled to take proceedings by which the lawfulne\nss of his detention shall be decided speedily by a court and his release ordered if the detention is not lawful.’\n [1985] QB 251\n Which allow legal representation for disciplinary hearings in certain circumstances, including where there is referral to an\n independent adjudicator.\n \n‘Transforming legal aid: delivering a mor\ne credible and efficient system\n’\n, para 3.18.\n See the Report on an unannounced inspection of  HMP Bristol by HM Chief Inspector of Prisons, available here:  \nhttp://www.justice.gov.uk/downloads/publications/inspectorate-reports/hmipris/prison-and-yoi-inspections/bristol/\nbristol-2013.pdf\n. \n \nTransforming Legal Aid: delivering a more credible and efficient system\n, para 3.15.\n \n‘Transforming legal aid: delivering a more \ncredible and efficient system’\n, \npara 3.69.\n \nMoJ consultation, \n‘\nJudicial Review – Proposals for further\n reform\n’\n,\n September 2013,\n para 125.\n \nJudicial Review: proposals for reform\n.\n See Liberty’s response to the proposals, available at: \nhttp://www.liberty-human-rights.org.uk/pdfs/policy13/liberty-s-submission-to-the-moj-s-consultation-on-judicia\nl-review-jan-2013-.pdf\n. \n Chris Grayling, \nThe judicial review system is not a promotional tool for countless Left-wing campaigners,\n \nhttp://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2413135/CHRIS-GRAYLING-Judicial-review-promotional-tool-Left-wing-campaigners.ht\nml\n. \n Ibid., para 3.61.\n Transcript available at \nhttp://www.publiclawproject.org.uk/documents/TranscriptChrisGraylingToday.pdf\n Response to the Government’s c\nonsultation paper: Transforming legal aid, prepared by the Public Law Project, para 2, available at \nhttp://www.publiclawproject.org.uk/\ndocuments/Draft_response_re_legal_aid_for_jr_conditional_on_permission.pdf\n \n‘Transforming legal aid: delivering a more credible and efficient system’\n,\n para 3.84.\n&#xa0;\n"